                     <note xml:lang="en">This manuscript was collected by Moses Wilhelm Shapira
                        (1830–1884). He was a dealer of antiquities and manuscripts who sold his
                        goods from a store in the Old City of Jerusalem. He is most known for the
                        controversy created among scholars over his purported scrolls of the book of
                        Deuteronomy and fake Moabite pottery; at the end of his life, he was
                        publicly disgraced as a fraudster. The sources of the manuscripts he sold
                        are not clear. In The Athenaeum no. 2855, dated July 15, 1882, Shapira
                        declared that his sources preferred to remain anonymous. Because of the
                        similarity of Shapira’s manuscripts to those sold by Abraham Firkovitch to
                        the Imperial Public Library in St. Petersburg, it has been argued that
                        Shapira also acquired his manuscripts from the Qaraite synagogue in Cairo.
                        (David Sklare, “A Guide to Collections of Karaite Manuscripts,” in Karaite
                        Judaism: A Guide to its History and Literary Sources, edited by Meira
                        Polliack (Leiden: Brill, 2003), pp. 893–924 [p. 896]; On the provenance of
                        Shapira's manuscripts, see the introduction in Reinhart Hoerning, Six
                        Karaite Manuscripts (London: Williams and Norgate, 1889), V.) Shapira
                        prepared an inventory, now at Staatsbibliothek zu Berlin, Ms. or. fol. 1342,
                        of the manuscripts he hoped to sell to institutional libraries. A
                        transcription may be found in the "Heritage data'' section. Shapira sold his
                        manuscripts to the British Museum (now British Library), London, between
                        1877 and 1883. Overall, the British Library owns some 200 Qaraite
                        manuscripts which can be traced back to Shapira. However, the volumes do not
                        always align with Shapira's catalogue; the librarians of the nineteenth
                        century rebound and combined incomplete and separate leafs into complete
                        books. Other libraries where Shapira manuscripts are housed today include
                        the Staatsbibliothek zu Berlin and the Sutro Library, the San Francisco
                        branch of the California State Library. </note>
